Due notice of proceedings is such a fundamental part of natural justice that decisions exercising the discretion to delay, or dispense with, service will be rare. Typically they will require circumstances of urgency (see 
[25.1.15]
), actual or apprehended misconduct by the person to be served (see 
[25.11.5]–[ 25.11.15]
). Sometimes the exercise of the discretion may be justified by the effect of disclosure on the health of the person to be served or by the likelihood that the interests of non-parties may be adversely affected by service of the proceedings: Re Elm (2006) 36 Fam LR 257; [2006] NSWSC 1137;  BC200608771  (court ordered delay in serving copies of summons, notice of motion and affidavits until after the birth of a child at risk of disease at birth — fear that the mother would not attend hospital if given notice of intention to treat the child).
